<subSubSection pageId="38" pageNumber="39" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="38.[151,1440,151,1869]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,223,248]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Description.</emphasis>
<typeStatus box="[354,458,223,248]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Holotype</typeStatus>
poorly preserved with body wall and many chaetae damaged, pale brown in colour, anterior fragment of 9 segments 
<quantity box="[531,599,260,285]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" unit="mm" value="2.0">2 mm</quantity>
long, 
<quantity box="[676,765,260,285]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" unit="mm" value="0.5">0.5 mm</quantity>
wide excluding buccal tentacles, mid-body fragment of 7 segments 
<quantity box="[266,335,295,320]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.0" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" unit="mm" value="2.0">2 mm</quantity>
long, 
<quantity box="[414,504,295,320]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" unit="mm" value="0.5">0.5 mm</quantity>
wide, poorly preserved, these 2 fragments may have been connected originally giving a total of 16 segments. Sex unknown.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="38.[151,1440,151,1869]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">
Dorsum anteriorly smooth. Venter anteriorly with mid-ventral groove and poorly defined ventro-lateral pads; pads more-or-less smooth. Mid-ventral groove from segment 3 (
<figureCitation box="[870,966,404,429]" captionStart="FIGURE 16" captionStartId="37.[151,250,1825,1847]" captionTargetBox="[163,1428,203,1790]" captionTargetId="figure-69@37.[151,1436,193,1804]" captionTargetPageId="37" captionText="FIGURE 16. Polycirrus clavatus (Kinberg). Holotype NRS 993. a. Anterior ventral view. b. Right side anterior lateral view of notopodium, chaetiger 2. c. Notochaeta from chaetiger 2. d. Lateral and ventral view of uncini from chaetiger 3. e. Lateral and frontal views of uncini from mid-body chaetiger." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4948420" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4948420/files/figure.png" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Fig. 16a</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="38.[151,1440,151,1869]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">
Buccal tentacles of 
<specimenCount box="[436,552,440,464]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" type="generic" typeStatus="types">two types</specimenCount>
, with few remaining attached: (1) cylindrical, thickened distally, distinctly grooved and (2) cylindrical, uniformly thin, weakly grooved, both arising at junction between prostomium and upper lip. Upper lip prominent medial lobe with slight lateral expansions at base forming enclosed diverticulae, margin of medial lobe straight; oral surface glandular and ciliated. Outer lower lip subconical lobe protruding above venter, tessellated (
<figureCitation box="[440,536,583,608]" captionStart="FIGURE 16" captionStartId="37.[151,250,1825,1847]" captionTargetBox="[163,1428,203,1790]" captionTargetId="figure-69@37.[151,1436,193,1804]" captionTargetPageId="37" captionText="FIGURE 16. Polycirrus clavatus (Kinberg). Holotype NRS 993. a. Anterior ventral view. b. Right side anterior lateral view of notopodium, chaetiger 2. c. Notochaeta from chaetiger 2. d. Lateral and ventral view of uncini from chaetiger 3. e. Lateral and frontal views of uncini from mid-body chaetiger." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4948420" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4948420/files/figure.png" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Fig. 16a</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="38.[151,1440,151,1869]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">
Notochaetigerous segments at least 14, extending to segment 16 (
<typeStatus box="[1008,1108,620,645]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">holotype</typeStatus>
broken after segment 16). Notopodia digitiform, prechaetal lobe low, postchaetal lobe digitiform, longer than prechaetal (
<figureCitation box="[1316,1423,655,680]" captionStart="FIGURE 16" captionStartId="37.[151,250,1825,1847]" captionTargetBox="[163,1428,203,1790]" captionTargetId="figure-69@37.[151,1436,193,1804]" captionTargetPageId="37" captionText="FIGURE 16. Polycirrus clavatus (Kinberg). Holotype NRS 993. a. Anterior ventral view. b. Right side anterior lateral view of notopodium, chaetiger 2. c. Notochaeta from chaetiger 2. d. Lateral and ventral view of uncini from chaetiger 3. e. Lateral and frontal views of uncini from mid-body chaetiger." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4948420" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4948420/files/figure.png" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Fig. 16b</figureCitation>
). Notochaetae within a chaetiger consisting of 
<specimenCount box="[682,782,692,716]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" type="generic">one type</specimenCount>
(chaetigers 4, 14 examined), gradually elongating from dorsal to ventral, pinnate, posteriorly same form as those anteriorly (
<figureCitation box="[914,1010,727,752]" captionStart="FIGURE 16" captionStartId="37.[151,250,1825,1847]" captionTargetBox="[163,1428,203,1790]" captionTargetId="figure-69@37.[151,1436,193,1804]" captionTargetPageId="37" captionText="FIGURE 16. Polycirrus clavatus (Kinberg). Holotype NRS 993. a. Anterior ventral view. b. Right side anterior lateral view of notopodium, chaetiger 2. c. Notochaeta from chaetiger 2. d. Lateral and ventral view of uncini from chaetiger 3. e. Lateral and frontal views of uncini from mid-body chaetiger." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4948420" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4948420/files/figure.png" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Fig. 16c</figureCitation>
). Neurochaetae beginning on segment 4 or 5 (left-right side variation). Neuropodial tori ridge-like, similar along body. Uncini with moderately long neck and undulating base (Type 2, but see Comments), teeth above main fang arranged in double transverse series (MF:1:7) enlarged median tooth above main fang present, subrostral process absent (
<figureCitation box="[1101,1226,836,861]" captionStart="FIGURE 16" captionStartId="37.[151,250,1825,1847]" captionTargetBox="[163,1428,203,1790]" captionTargetId="figure-69@37.[151,1436,193,1804]" captionTargetPageId="37" captionText="FIGURE 16. Polycirrus clavatus (Kinberg). Holotype NRS 993. a. Anterior ventral view. b. Right side anterior lateral view of notopodium, chaetiger 2. c. Notochaeta from chaetiger 2. d. Lateral and ventral view of uncini from chaetiger 3. e. Lateral and frontal views of uncini from mid-body chaetiger." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4948420" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4948420/files/figure.png" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Fig. 16d–e</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="38.[151,1440,151,1869]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">
Nephridial papillae present, globular. Pre-gular membrane nephridial papillae present on segments 3, 4. Postgular membrane nephridial papillae present, extending from segment 5 to 6; situated at ventral base of notopodia (
<figureCitation box="[159,255,943,968]" captionStart="FIGURE 16" captionStartId="37.[151,250,1825,1847]" captionTargetBox="[163,1428,203,1790]" captionTargetId="figure-69@37.[151,1436,193,1804]" captionTargetPageId="37" captionText="FIGURE 16. Polycirrus clavatus (Kinberg). Holotype NRS 993. a. Anterior ventral view. b. Right side anterior lateral view of notopodium, chaetiger 2. c. Notochaeta from chaetiger 2. d. Lateral and ventral view of uncini from chaetiger 3. e. Lateral and frontal views of uncini from mid-body chaetiger." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4948420" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4948420/files/figure.png" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Fig. 16a</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="38" pageNumber="39" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="38.[151,1440,151,1869]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,335,980,1005]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Comments.</emphasis>
There is some confusion in the literature on the type locality of 
<emphasis box="[1067,1196,980,1005]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kinberg" authorityYear="1867" baseAuthorityName="Kinberg" baseAuthorityYear="1867" box="[1067,1192,980,1005]" class="Polychaeta" family="Terebellidae" genus="Polycirrus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="clavatus">P. clavatus</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
Most authors simply refer it to 
<collectingCountry box="[265,336,1015,1040]" name="Brazil" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Brazil</collectingCountry>
, but 
<bibRefCitation author="Carrerette, O. &amp; Nogueira, J. M. M." box="[391,727,1015,1040]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" pagination="146 - 172" refId="ref59726" refString="Carrerette, O. &amp; Nogueira, J. M. M. (2013) Four new species of Polycirrus Grube, 1850 (Polychaeta: Terebellidae) from Campos Basin, southeastern Brazil. Zootaxa, 3626 (1), 146 - 172. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 3626.1.6" type="journal article" year="2013">Carrerette &amp; Nogueira (2013)</bibRefCitation>
appear to have introduced the more specific locality of Rio de Janiero. However, the type description clearly states that it was found from latitude 
<geoCoordinate box="[1082,1124,1052,1077]" degrees="9" direction="south" orientation="latitude" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" precision="55555" value="-9.0">9°S</geoCoordinate>
, which puts it in the present State of 
<collectingRegion box="[243,335,1087,1112]" country="Brazil" name="Alagoas" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Alagoas</collectingRegion>
in northeast 
<collectingCountry box="[480,552,1087,1112]" name="Brazil" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Brazil</collectingCountry>
. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Kinberg" authorityYear="1867" baseAuthorityName="Kinberg" baseAuthorityYear="1867" box="[562,780,1087,1112]" class="Polychaeta" family="Terebellidae" genus="Polycirrus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="clavatus">
<emphasis box="[562,780,1087,1112]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Polycirrus clavatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is very similar to two other species described from 
<collectingCountry box="[1360,1433,1087,1112]" name="Brazil" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Brazil</collectingCountry>
: 
<taxonomicName authority="Garraffoni &amp; Costa, 2003" authorityName="Garraffoni &amp; Costa" authorityYear="2003" box="[151,608,1124,1149]" class="Polychaeta" family="Terebellidae" genus="Polycirrus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="abrolhensis">
<emphasis box="[151,310,1124,1149]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">P. abrolhensis</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Garraffoni, A. R. S. &amp; Costa, E. M." box="[317,608,1124,1149]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" pagination="1 - 7" refId="ref60401" refString="Garraffoni, A. R. S. &amp; Costa, E. M. (2003) Two new species of Polycirrus (Polychaeta, Terebellidae) from Abrolhos Archipelago, Brazil. Zootaxa, 297, 1 - 7." type="journal article" year="2003">Garraffoni &amp; Costa, 2003</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
from the Abrolhos Archipelago (
<geoCoordinate box="[990,1046,1124,1149]" degrees="18" direction="south" orientation="latitude" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" precision="55555" value="-18.0">18°S</geoCoordinate>
) in 
<quantity box="[1093,1151,1124,1149]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" unit="m" value="10.0">10 m</quantity>
of water (see Comments for this species), and 
<taxonomicName authority="Carrerette &amp; Nogueira, 2013" authorityName="Carrerette &amp; Nogueira" authorityYear="2013" box="[400,864,1159,1184]" class="Polychaeta" family="Terebellidae" genus="Polycirrus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="habitats">
<emphasis box="[400,520,1159,1184]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">P. habitats</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Carrerette, O. &amp; Nogueira, J. M. M." box="[531,864,1159,1184]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" pagination="146 - 172" refId="ref59726" refString="Carrerette, O. &amp; Nogueira, J. M. M. (2013) Four new species of Polycirrus Grube, 1850 (Polychaeta: Terebellidae) from Campos Basin, southeastern Brazil. Zootaxa, 3626 (1), 146 - 172. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 3626.1.6" type="journal article" year="2013">Carrerette &amp; Nogueira, 2013</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, collected from off 
<collectingRegion box="[1094,1261,1159,1184]" country="Brazil" name="Rio de Janeiro" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Rio de Janeiro</collectingRegion>
in 
<specimenCount box="[1302,1383,1159,1184]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" type="generic">
<quantity box="[1302,1379,1159,1184]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.2" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" unit="m" value="720.0">720 m</quantity>
.
</specimenCount>
The similarity with the latter species is in fact quite striking, and based on a comparison between the 
<typeStatus box="[1304,1402,1196,1221]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">holotype</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName authority="Kinberg, 1867" authorityName="Kinberg" authorityYear="1867" box="[151,527,1231,1256]" class="Polychaeta" family="Terebellidae" genus="Cyaxares" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="clavatus">
<emphasis box="[151,356,1231,1256]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Cyaxares clavatus</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Kinberg, J. G. H." box="[365,527,1231,1256]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" pagination="337 - 355" refId="ref62079" refString="Kinberg, J. G. H. (1867) Annulata nova. In: Ofversigt af Kongl. Vetenskaps-Akademiens Forhandlinggar. Tjugondetredje. Argangen Med Tretton Taflor. Stockholm, no. 9, pp. 337 - 355." type="journal article" year="1867">Kinberg, 1867</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
and the comprehensive description of 
<bibRefCitation author="Carrerette, O. &amp; Nogueira, J. M. M." box="[967,1304,1231,1256]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" pagination="146 - 172" refId="ref59726" refString="Carrerette, O. &amp; Nogueira, J. M. M. (2013) Four new species of Polycirrus Grube, 1850 (Polychaeta: Terebellidae) from Campos Basin, southeastern Brazil. Zootaxa, 3626 (1), 146 - 172. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 3626.1.6" type="journal article" year="2013">Carrerette &amp; Nogueira (2013)</bibRefCitation>
we suggest formal synonymy of the two species. According to 
<bibRefCitation author="Carrerette, O. &amp; Nogueira, J. M. M." box="[767,1117,1268,1293]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" pagination="146 - 172" refId="ref59726" refString="Carrerette, O. &amp; Nogueira, J. M. M. (2013) Four new species of Polycirrus Grube, 1850 (Polychaeta: Terebellidae) from Campos Basin, southeastern Brazil. Zootaxa, 3626 (1), 146 - 172. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 3626.1.6" type="journal article" year="2013">Carrerette &amp; Nogueira (2013)</bibRefCitation>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Carrerette &amp; Nogueira" authorityYear="2013" box="[1129,1252,1268,1293]" class="Polychaeta" family="Terebellidae" genus="Polycirrus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="habitats">
<emphasis box="[1129,1252,1268,1293]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">P. habitats</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from 
<taxonomicName authority="Kinberg, 1867" authorityName="Kinberg" authorityYear="1867" class="Polychaeta" family="Terebellidae" genus="Cyaxares" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="clavatus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">P. clavatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in having notopodia extending to segment 17 (i.e., 15 pairs) and neuropodia beginning on segment 9 (an additional difference mentioned in their key is the presence of both limbate and pinnate notochaetae in 
<taxonomicName authority="Kinberg, 1867" authorityName="Kinberg" authorityYear="1867" box="[1308,1429,1340,1365]" class="Polychaeta" family="Terebellidae" genus="Cyaxares" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="clavatus">
<emphasis box="[1308,1429,1340,1365]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">P. clavatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but present observations indicate that 
<taxonomicName authority="Kinberg, 1867" authorityName="Kinberg" authorityYear="1867" box="[579,700,1375,1400]" class="Polychaeta" family="Terebellidae" genus="Cyaxares" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="clavatus">
<emphasis box="[579,700,1375,1400]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">P. clavatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
only has pinnate notochaetae like 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Carrerette &amp; Nogueira" authorityYear="2013" box="[1093,1212,1375,1400]" class="Polychaeta" family="Terebellidae" genus="Polycirrus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="habitats">
<emphasis box="[1093,1212,1375,1400]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">P. habitats</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). As can be seen in 
<tableCitation box="[151,234,1412,1437]" captionStart="TABLE 1" captionStartId="5.[151,239,296,319]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="TABLE 1. Literature reports of intraspecific variation in the number of notochaetigerous segments and start of neuropodia in Polycirrus species. Mean of ranges indicated. Only reports indicating numbers of specimens examined are included." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/DF1B663CFF96FFDAFF66A275C6FEA290" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" tableUuid="DF1B663CFF96FFDAFF66A275C6FEA290">Table 1</tableCitation>
the mean variation within a 
<taxonomicName box="[555,761,1412,1437]" class="Polychaeta" family="Terebellidae" genus="Polycirrus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis box="[555,673,1412,1437]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Polycirrus</emphasis>
species
</taxonomicName>
in terms of number of notopodia is about five segments and for the start of the neuropodia is about four segments, so that 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Carrerette &amp; Nogueira" authorityYear="2013" box="[840,958,1447,1472]" class="Polychaeta" family="Terebellidae" genus="Polycirrus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="habitats">
<emphasis box="[840,958,1447,1472]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">P. habitats</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
falls in the range of variation expected for 
<taxonomicName authority="Kinberg, 1867" authorityName="Kinberg" authorityYear="1867" box="[151,273,1484,1509]" class="Polychaeta" family="Terebellidae" genus="Cyaxares" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="clavatus">
<emphasis box="[151,273,1484,1509]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">P. clavatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. As there appear to be no other differences between the two species, apart from the uncini (which are taken from different parts of the body and therefore would be expected to be different), we propose that 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Carrerette &amp; Nogueira" authorityYear="2013" box="[1318,1436,1519,1544]" class="Polychaeta" family="Terebellidae" genus="Polycirrus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="habitats">
<emphasis box="[1318,1436,1519,1544]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">P. habitats</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
should be relegated to a junior synonymy.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="38.[151,1440,151,1869]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">
The 
<typeStatus box="[253,351,1591,1616]" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">holotype</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName authority="Kinberg, 1867" authorityName="Kinberg" authorityYear="1867" box="[395,519,1591,1616]" class="Polychaeta" family="Terebellidae" genus="Cyaxares" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Terebellida" pageId="38" pageNumber="39" phylum="Annelida" rank="species" species="clavatus">
<emphasis box="[395,519,1591,1616]" italics="true" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">P. clavatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
consists of only 16 segments, so we were unable to observe the uncini of the posterior body. Those of the anterior body (
<figureCitation box="[642,764,1628,1653]" captionStart="FIGURE 16" captionStartId="37.[151,250,1825,1847]" captionTargetBox="[163,1428,203,1790]" captionTargetId="figure-69@37.[151,1436,193,1804]" captionTargetPageId="37" captionText="FIGURE 16. Polycirrus clavatus (Kinberg). Holotype NRS 993. a. Anterior ventral view. b. Right side anterior lateral view of notopodium, chaetiger 2. c. Notochaeta from chaetiger 2. d. Lateral and ventral view of uncini from chaetiger 3. e. Lateral and frontal views of uncini from mid-body chaetiger." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4948420" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4948420/files/figure.png" pageId="38" pageNumber="39">Fig. 16d, e</figureCitation>
) however are not typical of Type 2 as defined by 
<bibRefCitation author="Glasby, C. J. &amp; Glasby, T. M." pageId="38" pageNumber="39" pagination="237 - 253" refId="ref60498" refString="Glasby, C. J. &amp; Glasby, T. M. (2006) Two types of uncini in Polycirrus (Polychaeta: Terebellidae: Polycirrinae) revealed using geometric morphometrics. Journal of Natural History, 40 (5 - 6), 237 - 253. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1080 / 00222930600627137" type="journal article" year="2006">Glasby &amp; Glasby (2006)</bibRefCitation>
, which has an elongate rostrum, long neck and arched (concave) base. Nevertheless, the results of their morphometric analysis utilising all components of shape variation placed these uncini in the Type 2 category. It is likely that the uncini of the posterior body have a more typical Type 2 shape. As noted in the section on morphological characters, at least three other species show the combination of Type 2 uncini and early start of uncini occurring on poorly developed neuropodia. In addition, analysis of co-varying notochaetal characters by these authors provided further support for the grouping of this species with other species bearing Type 2 uncini.
</paragraph>
